{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n\nThe 2026-07-08 principal-architect audit (Reliability finding #3) found that three documented reconciler safety mechanisms are implemented, tested, and **never called in production** — the safety they promise is illusory, and the current epic's children do not cover them:\n\n1. **Create->label crash window double-creates Jira issues.** `dispatch_one.py:241-256` runs `create_issue` -> then adds the `rebar-id:` label the JQL dedup keys on -> then binds in memory only; bindings persist only at end of pass (`reconcile.py:1068`). A hard crash between create and label leaves an orphan issue invisible to dedup; the re-run creates a duplicate.\n2. **The write-ahead/recovery protocol is dead code - and miswired.** `binding_store.py:6-16` documents pending->confirm; `bind_pending` has zero production callers, and `run_differs.py:351` passes the applier module (which has no `search_issues`) as the client to `recover_pending_bindings`, so real recovery `AttributeError`s into a fail-open swallow (`run_differs.py:352-357`).\n3. **Crashed pass deadlocks reconciliation forever.** Lease `steal()` is implemented and tested (`_ref_lock.py:516-535`) but the held-ref path unconditionally exits 3 (`__main__.py:499-505`); after a SIGKILL the remote `refs/reconciler/lock` persists until an operator hand-deletes it.\n4. **The wrapped write path never retries transient HTTP failures.** The REST helper re-raises every `HTTPError` (`acli_rest.py:61-63`) and the applier's `_call_with_retry` only retries `JiraAPIError` (`dispatch_one.py:100-144`), which the raw-`HTTPError` REST path never raises. Sibling C4 (lambswool-shaded-eider) fixes only the bulk-path 429 parity - it does not revive the wrapped write path.\n\n## What\n\nWire each mechanism into its intended call site, smallest-change-first:\n\n1. **Revive the retry layer WITHOUT a boundary translation.** Do NOT translate `HTTPError`->`JiraAPIError` at `acli_rest.py` - that would silently break the 8+ callers that catch raw `urllib.error.HTTPError` from the REST path (outbound_differ.py, apply_handlers.py:147/151 - which explicitly needs raw 404, acli_graph.py, fetcher.py, inbound_probe.py, acli_cli_ops.py, dispatch_one.py:484, applier.py). Instead, extend the applier's `_call_with_retry` (dispatch_one.py:100-144) to ALSO recognize a retryable `urllib.error.HTTPError` (429 honoring `Retry-After`; 5xx with jittered backoff) in addition to `JiraAPIError`, leaving acli_rest's raw-`HTTPError` raise UNCHANGED. Non-retryable statuses (4xx except 429) propagate raw exactly as today. Zero blast radius on the raw-HTTPError callers.\n2. **Write-safety via a per-retry dedup guard on CREATE (comments scoped out).** `_call_with_retry` re-invokes the same callable; the rebar-id JQL dedup search (dispatch_one.py:196) runs ONCE before the wrapper, so a mid-flight 429/5xx on `create_issue` could re-send and double-create. Wrap `create_issue` in a dedup-aware callable that RE-RUNS the rebar-id JQL search at the START of every retry attempt and short-circuits to the existing issue if the key now exists. Comments are deliberately NOT retried (see Design decision D2). Idempotent ops (update/transition/label) retry directly.\n3. **Deterministic write-ahead recovery.** Persist a `bind_pending` record BEFORE `create_issue`; once create returns a key, record the key into the pending binding and persist AGAIN BEFORE `add_label`. Fix `recover_pending_bindings` (called at `run_differs.py:351`) - it currently passes the `applier` MODULE (no `search_issues`) -> `AttributeError` into a fail-open swallow. Pass a real client (the `AcliClient` exposing `search_issues`). Recovery becomes deterministic (see D1): a pending record that already carries a `jira_key` is confirmed with NO Jira search (retro-attaching the label idempotently); a keyless pending record falls back to the `search_issues` rebar-id-label lookup. Make recovery failures LOUD: emit a bridge alert via the existing `alert_store` channel (the 24h-deduped, fail-open path `run_differs._emit_outbound_field_alerts` uses) AND set a nonzero `recovery_failures` pass-result/`sync_pass_end` tally - instead of the silent swallow.\n4. **Crashed-pass lease steal.** In `__main__.py`'s held-lock path (`__main__.py:499-505`), attempt `steal()` (the sanctioned skew-proof expiry primitive - `_ref_lock.py:516-535`) instead of unconditional exit 3: a stale lease (holder made no `(oid,fence)` progress over one lease window) is stolen and the pass proceeds; a live holder (progress observed) or a re-freed ref falls through to acquire/exit-3 as appropriate.\n\n## Scope\n\nIn: `dispatch_one.py` (`_call_with_retry` HTTPError-aware + dedup-guarded create callable + bind_pending/key-persist before/after create + single-attempt comment post), `run_differs.py` (hoist the `AcliClient` above recovery + recover_pending_bindings client fix + loud failures + recovery_failures tally), `binding_store.py` (record jira_key into a pending record; deterministic recovery branch that confirms keyed pending records without a Jira search), `reconcile.py` (`recovery_failures` in the pass result + `sync_pass_end` log), `__main__.py` (`steal_pass_lock` in the held-lock path), plus a thin `advisory.steal_pass_lock` wrapper in `_advisory_lock.py`, and tests under `tests/scripts/bridge/` and `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/`. Read-only (relied on, not changed): `acli_rest.py` (raw HTTPError raise UNCHANGED - verified non-breaking for its 8+ catchers), `_ref_lock.py` (`steal()` already implemented). Out: bulk-path 429 parity (C4 owns it), inbound status mapping (audit-remediation epic), `_call_with_backoff` revival (C4).\n\n## Design decisions (round 4, resolved from code facts)\n\n- **D1 - create->label window is closed DETERMINISTICALLY, not by fuzzy search.** acli `create_issue` cannot carry the rebar-id label atomically (the no-priority path has no `--label`; `--labels` is a destructive SET-REPLACE - acli_graph.py:122-127), so an atomic-labelled create is not available. Instead the pending binding records the `jira_key` the instant `create_issue` returns (persisted before `add_label`), so `recover_pending_bindings` confirms a keyed pending record with NO Jira search - deterministic, no summary-matching heuristic. Only a keyless pending record (crash before/during create) uses the existing label `search_issues` fallback. This moves `binding_store.py` into scope (a small keyed-pending setter + a recovery branch).\n- **D2 - comments are scoped OUT of the retry/dedup guard.** There is no cheap Jira-side idempotency key for a comment (comments are posted verbatim, no marker today - acli_cli_ops.py:469-492), and a duplicate comment is low-harm vs. a duplicate issue; embedding a visible `[rebar-cid]` trailer would pollute every synced comment. So comments are posted with a SINGLE attempt (not wrapped in the HTTP-retrying `_call_with_retry`); a failed post is recorded to the existing non-fatal `comment_errors` path and re-emitted by the comment differ on the next pass (eventually-consistent). This guarantees no duplicate comment.\n- **D3 - lease expiry uses `steal()` itself, not a wall-clock `pass_lock_is_expired`.** `_ref_lock` deliberately treats `heartbeat_ns` as diagnostic-only and determines expiry behaviorally via `steal()` (read -> sleep one `lease_secs` -> re-check whether `(oid,fence)` advanced). So the held-lock path calls a thin `advisory.steal_pass_lock` -> `_ref_lock.steal()`: a returned new-oid means the lease was stale (stolen -> proceed); `None` means the holder is live or the ref freed. `sleep_fn` is injected in tests to avoid the real lease-length sleep.\n- **D4 - `recovery_failures` is a pass-result + `sync_pass_end` tally.** No such key exists today. Recovery runs at pass startup; the count is threaded from `recover_pending_bindings` up into `reconcile.py`'s result dict (beside `mutation_failures`) and the `sync_pass_end` log - not into the mutation-action `manifest_renderer` totals (which are about create/update/delete actions, not startup recovery).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `_call_with_retry` retries a retryable `HTTPError`: 429 honoring `Retry-After` when the header is PRESENT and falling back to jittered exponential backoff when it is ABSENT (Jira Cloud does not guarantee the header); 5xx with jittered backoff; non-retryable 4xx re-raised. WITHOUT translating at `acli_rest.py` - a test asserts the raw `HTTPError` raise from `acli_rest` is unchanged so the 8+ raw-`HTTPError` catchers (e.g. apply_handlers.py:151's 404 path) still see raw `HTTPError`. Both the header-present and header-absent 429 paths are tested. Proof: `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/test_retry_httperror.py`.\n- [ ] The non-idempotent **create** re-runs its rebar-id JQL dedup check at the START of every retry attempt and short-circuits to the existing issue if the key now exists - a test injects a 429 AFTER a create that already landed and asserts NO duplicate issue is created. **Comments are posted with a single attempt** (D2): a test injects an `HTTPError` 429 on `add_comment` and asserts `add_comment` is called exactly once and the failure is recorded to `comment_errors` (no duplicate post). Proof: `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/test_create_dedup_guard.py`.\n- [ ] Write-ahead is deterministic (D1): `bind_pending(local_id)` is written and the store persisted BEFORE `create_issue`; once `create_issue` returns a key, the key is recorded into the pending binding and persisted BEFORE `add_label`. `recover_pending_bindings` confirms any pending record that already carries a `jira_key` (retro-attaching the label idempotently) with NO Jira search, so a hard crash between create and label yields NO duplicate; a keyless pending record falls back to the `search_issues` rebar-id-label lookup (confirm if found, else unbind). Tests: (a) crash after create+key-persist but before label -> next pass confirms, no duplicate; (b) crash before create -> fallback unbind/relabel. Proof: `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/test_write_ahead_recovery.py`.\n- [ ] `recover_pending_bindings` receives a client object exposing `search_issues` (the hoisted `AcliClient`, not the applier module); a recovery failure emits a bridge alert via the `alert_store` channel AND increments a nonzero `recovery_failures` tally on the pass result + `sync_pass_end` log, instead of the silent fail-open swallow. Proof: `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/test_recovery_loud_failures.py`.\n- [ ] A pass encountering a stale (expired) lease steals it via `steal()` and proceeds; a live unexpired lease (holder progress observed) falls through to exit 3 (both covered by tests with an injected `sleep_fn`). Proof: `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/test_lock_steal.py`.\n- [ ] Both test locations green: `python -m pytest tests/scripts/bridge/ -q` AND `python -m pytest tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/ -q`.\n"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783570448975397001,"uuid":"1957bb0d-cfeb-4def-9684-cc9666db0225"}